text: So when I came home and didn't tell my family and then I went back to work in the morning and the guy who came, a robber, his family, I knew them all. They were staying in the back of the station. So his aunt came and asked me what happened. So I didn't know that she was his aunt. So I told him the story of what happened. So later I found out that that was his nephew. So then, I mean, he was caught and he got to jail and then he killed two other people over there and then he went to jail again. But for me, I didn't have any fear, sort of, you know. So that was it. So this next time I was, didn't happen. Didn't happen anything to me. I was doing something in my house, two-story building, and I went up the top where the gutter was. I'm doing something and I fell backward on the concrete. And all that happened was that I broke three ribs. I drove myself to the hospital and when I went, they laid me on gunnery and I couldn't move that time. So they had the x-ray and they found there was three ribs broken. That was it. Nothing else. And how far did you fall? About two stories. About three feet. About three feet. Twenty-five, thirty feet, I suppose. You know, I'm not sure, but two-story building was our house in San Jose. So that was my other escape. I could have broken my neck or some other back injury or whatever, nothing happened. So then, I mean, this cancer came. First time, that was also a coincidence that they found it so early, that I used to hike from my house to the bay. Fourth of July every year, twenty-two miles. It's ten miles from here to the bay and then two miles around the hills, in Coyote Hills over there. So it was around about twenty-two miles. And some of my club hikers used to meet me along the way and go there and come back. So that Fourth of July, two years ago, I did the same. It was too hot. So I didn't eat enough food. Or not enough drink. So I lost some weight. So I went to my Tai Chi class and the lady, teacher over there, she said, Ali, have you lost some weight? I said, no, I don't think so. She said, yes, I do see that you lost some weight. So after the class, I went in the senior center, I went on the scale and found that I lost five, six pounds. So luckily, next day I was going to see my doctor for some other reason. And I just mentioned to him, I said, I lost some weight. And he knew that I do a lot of exercise, I was going to the gym as well, and doing hikes and all that. So he could have said to me, well, you do so much exercise, go back and eat enough food and you'll be okay. And that's what happened, actually, that when I found out I lost weight, I ate regularly. So I gained my weight again. But he, the doctor, sent me straight away to CT scan without asking any questions. So in the CT scan. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Right hand kidney was out of shape. So it was not so clear. So he sent me for MRI and that's, they found that there was growth there. But very early, it was only two centimeter. So he said, there's two options. Either I take my kidney out or stay there until it get out of hands or away or grew more. Then eventually they have to take the kidney out because they can't do a biopsy on a kidney. so I told him I said just take the kidney out because I don't want to live with worry all the time so I went to the hospital in Hayward Kaiser so there they took my kidney out so I was okay then there was no post treatment because it was found so early and I was fine I was doing say my normal exercise hikes and all that and then about 3 months ago the same cancer came back and got my clavicle joint under the chin so I saw a lump there so I thought I injured myself doing exercise so I went to the doctor and told him I said it's a lump there so I think I injured myself because I feel a little pain as well in my clavicle joint so he said no I want a biopsy on it so he sent me for biopsy and there they found the same cancer kidney cancer so what happens that doctor told me that sometime the cancer cells escape from growth and they float around the body and they get attached to a red cell a blood cell and they get stronger and settle anywhere so luckily it was still out there so they would see it and it was easy to for the treatment for radiation so they sent me for radiation I went to radiation for 18 sessions so and it was easy to it went to remission so then I'm okay again so thank God you know this I'm still leading my kind of normal life five lives yeah five lives gone so maybe another two but by the time then I will be gone anyway no we don't have it yeah of course any other last thoughts?
